  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "Operaismo (Italian: workerism) is the political and intellectual tendency that emerged in Italy in the early 1960s, associated with the journals Quaderni Rossi (1961–1965) and Classe Operaia (1964–1967) and with figures including Raniero Panzieri, Mario Tronti, and Antonio Negri. Operaismo\u0026rsquo;s foundational move is a Copernican inversion of the relationship between capital and labor: rather than studying capital\u0026rsquo;s laws of motion and deriving the working class as a consequence, operaismo starts from working-class struggle and derives capital\u0026rsquo;s development as a response.\n",
  "name": "Operaismo",
